# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1993-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The 1883 season was the first in the history of the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team was founded earlier in the year as a replacement for the Worcester franchise.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] It was the first year Philadelphia was represented in the National League since the original Athletics were disbanded in 1876 after refusing to finish the season.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The American Association's Philadelphia Athletics had been founded a year earlier.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team opened the year managed by Bob Ferguson; however, he was fired as manager after a disappointing 4–13 start and replaced by Blondie Purcell.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team finished the season 17–81, worst in the National League.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies played their first game ever on April 2, 1883, and defeated the amateur Manayunk Ashlands in an exhibition game by the score of 11–0 at Recreation Park.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies hosted Providence at Recreation Park in their first regular season game on May 1, 1883.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] One thousand fans saw John Coleman start the game for the Phillies and relinquish the first hit in the first inning to Providence first baseman Joe Start.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies scored first and took a three to zero lead into the eighth inning when Providence scored four times to win the game.
[src:1993-world-series/1883-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies would lose their first eleven games, and not win their first game at home in Philadelphia until June 6, 1883.
[src:1993-world-series/1884-philadelphia-quakers-season] The 1884 season was the second in the history of the Philadelphia Quakers.
[src:1993-world-series/1885-philadelphia-quakers-season] The **1885 Philadelphia Quakers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1993-world-series/1885-philadelphia-quakers-season] The team finished with a record of 56–54, a distant third place in the National League, 30 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1993-world-series/1885-philadelphia-quakers-season] On June 1, 1885, nearly 10,000 fans filled the Phillies' Recreation Park to see the Phillies face the New York Giants, with fans crowded down the right and left field foul lines.
[src:1993-world-series/1886-philadelphia-quakers-season] The **1886 Philadelphia Phillies season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1993-world-series/1886-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 71–43, 14 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The **Philadelphia Quakers** team, also known as "the Phillies," opened its 1887 season by playing a home game in its new ballpark on Saturday, April 30 against the New York Giants.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] Multiple civic and business leaders were in attendance.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies held spring training in Savannah, Georgia, leaving Philadelphia on March 15, 1887 by train from Broad Street Station.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies trained in Savannah through March 25.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies opened their preseason City Series against the Athletics on April 4, 1887 at the Athletics' Jefferson Street Grounds.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] 9,183 tickets were sold to the game and an "immense crowd" turned out to see the Phillies win by a score of 10 to 2.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies moved into their new ballpark at 15th and Huntingdon Streets in April 1887.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The park was to have opened on April 4, 1887 for the City Series game against the Athletics but inclement weather delayed final construction.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies played their first game in the new ballpark on Saturday, April 30, 1887, the home opener against the New York Giants.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] 18,000 tickets were sold for the first game, with 13,000 in the stands and an additional 5,000 fans crowded onto the bicycle track which encircled the field and others in the terraces above left field.
[src:1993-world-series/1887-philadelphia-quakers-season] Philadelphia's Mayor Edwin Henry Fitler attended along with the city's political and business leadership, and many baseball leaders.
[src:1993-world-series/1888-philadelphia-quakers-season] The **1888 Philadelphia Phillies season** was the 6th season in the history of the franchise and second season playing home games at National League Park at Broad and Huntingdon Streets.
[src:1993-world-series/1888-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies held spring training in Cape May, New Jersey from March 19, 1888, to March 30, 1888.
[src:1993-world-series/1888-philadelphia-quakers-season] The Phillies stayed at the Chalfonte Hotel and practiced and played games games at the Cape May Athletic Park behind the hotel between Sewell and Benton Streets.
[src:1993-world-series/1888-philadelphia-quakers-season] When rain and snow barred outdoor work, Manager Harry Wright secured the use of the indoor Star Rink where the players practiced.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The **1993 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1993 season.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The 90th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff played between the defending World Series champion and American League (AL) champion Toronto Blue Jays and the National League (NL) champion Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays defeated the Phillies in six games, becoming the seventh franchise in MLB history to win back-to-back championships.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] With Toronto ahead three games to two in the Series, but trailing Game 6 by a score of 6–5 in the bottom of the ninth inning, Joe Carter hit a game-winning three-run home run to clinch Toronto's second consecutive championship (the first team to repeat as champions since the 1977–78 Yankees).
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] This was only the second Series concluded by such a home run (the first was on a Bill Mazeroski home run for the Pittsburgh Pirates, in the bottom of the ninth in the seventh game of the 1960 World Series), and the first such occasion where a come-from-behind walk-off home run won a World Series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] This victory was the last major North American professional sports championship won by a Canadian team until the Toronto Raptors won the 2019 NBA Finals.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] This was the fourth World Series with games played entirely on artificial turf, following the series of 1980, 1985, and 1987.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] A fifth occurred in 2020, although that was a neutral-site series during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The sixth would be the 2023 World Series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Larry Andersen was the only member of the Phillies who had played for the team in its previous World Series appearance in 1983 (although he played for several other teams from 1986 to 1992).
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Darren Daulton had been a late season call-up in 1983, but only served as the bullpen catcher in the World Series that year.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] To date, this remains Toronto's last World Series victory, as well as the most recent championship in any of the four major leagues to be won by a Canadian team at their home venue.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Jays would not return to the World Series until 32 years later, in 2025.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] They also did not return to the playoffs after 1993 until 2015.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Nick Leyva, who was fired as the Phillies manager 13 games into the 1991 season after going 4–9, and replaced by Jim Fregosi, was the 3B coach for the Blue Jays.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Leyva was the AAA Syracuse manager, but got the call up to the MLB staff after regular 3B coach Rich Hacker was badly injured in a car crash in July.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Series' first game sent two staff aces—Curt Schilling for Philadelphia and Juan Guzman for Toronto—against one another.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The result was less than a pitcher's duel, however, as both teams scored early and often.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Philles struck first in the top of the first on RBI singles by John Kruk and Darren Daulton aided by two walks.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the bottom of the second, after two singles and a wild pitch, Paul Molitor's single and Tony Fernandez's groundout scored a run each to tie the game.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Phillies retook the lead in the fifth inning when Duncan tripled with one out and scored on a wild pitch, but White hit a home run to tie the game in the bottom of the inning.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The next inning, John Olerud hit a home run to put Toronto on top 5–4.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the seventh, after two one-out singles, Schilling was relieved by David West, who allowed an RBI double to White and two-run double to Roberto Alomar to pad Toronto's lead to 8–4.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Phillies got a run in the ninth when Kruk hit a leadoff single, moved to second on an error and scored on Jim Eisenreich's two-out single, but Duane Ward got Ricky Jordan to fly out to end the game as Toronto won 8–5.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Al Leiter pitched 2+2⁄3 innings—in relief of an erratic Juan Guzman, who walked four in just five innings—for his first World Series win.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Alomar made an amazing diving catch on a Lenny Dykstra looper behind first in the top of the fifth.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the second game of the Series, ALCS MVP Dave Stewart was on the mound for Toronto and Terry Mulholland started for Philadelphia.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Philadelphia jumped out to an early lead: in the third inning, After two walks, John Kruk and Dave Hollins hit back-to-back RBI singles, then Jim Eisenreich followed with a three-run home run to deep right-center to put them up 5–0.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Toronto cut the lead to 6–4 in the eighth when Paul Molitor hit a leadoff double off Roger Mason, stole third and scored on John Olerud's sacrifice fly off Mitch Williams.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Alomar then walked and stole second, but was caught stealing third to end the inning.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Williams then pitched a scoreless ninth as the Phillies won to tie the series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Mulholland pitched 5+2⁄3 innings, allowing three earned runs, for the win.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The West Chester University "Incomparable" Golden Rams Marching Band performed the pregame show for Game 3.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] As he had in the preceding World Series, when the 1993 edition moved into the National League ballpark Toronto manager Cito Gaston was faced with a decision regarding his designated hitter.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Against a left-handed pitcher, Gaston decided to stick with the right-handed veteran Molitor, but had left-hitting Olerud on the bench if needed later in the game.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays sent future Cy Young winner Pat Hentgen to the mound for Game 3.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Phillies countered with veteran Danny Jackson, who was one of the few Phillies that had pitched in a World Series; he was part of the 1985 Kansas City and 1990 Cincinnati teams that won World Series championships.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays struck for two runs before recording an out.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] After Rickey Henderson’s leadoff single and Devon White’s walk, Molitor tripled to drive them both in.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Joe Carter then extended the Toronto lead to 3–0 with a sacrifice fly, but Jackson got out of the inning by retiring Roberto Alomar and Tony Fernandez.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Phillies got two runners in scoring position with one out in their half of the first, with Mariano Duncan and John Kruk singling and an error by Carter enabling both runners to advance a base.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Hentgen ended the threat by striking out Dave Hollins and Darren Daulton; the Phillies only got one more man on base before the sixth inning.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Molitor struck again with two out in the fourth, hitting a solo home run to extend the lead to four.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Carter, Alomar, and Fernandez followed with singles to load the bases, but Jackson struck out Ed Sprague Jr. to end the inning without further damage.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Jackson would be lifted for a pinch hitter in the fifth.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the sixth, Phillies reliever Ben Rivera gave up a leadoff single to Alomar.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] With Fernandez up, the speedy second baseman stole second and third and scored on a sacrifice fly by his double-play partner.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Phillies got on the board in the bottom of the inning on a single by Jim Eisenreich that drove in Kruk.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] This was Hentgen’s last inning of work; Danny Cox would come on for the seventh.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the top of the seventh, Henderson hit a leadoff double, then scored on a triple by White.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] After a walk by Molitor and a Carter strikeout, Alomar's RBI single made it 7–1 in favor of Toronto.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Bobby Thigpen relieved Rivera and walked Fernandez before Sprague's sacrifice fly made it 8–1.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Phillies managed a run off Cox in the seventh, with a string of singles by Milt Thompson, Lenny Dykstra, and Duncan with one out resulting in Thompson scoring.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays finished their offensive output in the top of the ninth with an RBI triple by Alomar that scored Molitor and a single by Fernandez that followed to bring in Alomar.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Thompson hit a solo home run against Toronto closer Duane Ward in the bottom of the ninth to finish out the scoring, and the Blue Jays emerged with a 10–3 victory and a two-games-to-one lead in the series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the fourth game of the Series, Toronto sent Todd Stottlemyre to the mound while Philadelphia countered with Tommy Greene.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] It had been a rainy day in Philadelphia, which water-logged the aging turf at Veterans Stadium, making for particularly slippery conditions.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Toronto loaded the bases in the first on a double, walk and single.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Paul Molitor walked to force in a run before Tony Fernandez's single scored two more.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the bottom half, three walks loaded the bases for the Phillies before Jim Eisenreich walked to force in a run, then Milt Thompson's three-run triple put the Phillies up 4–3.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Lenny Dykstra's two-run home run next inning made it 6–3 Phillies.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the top of the third, after a one-out walk and single, consecutive RBI singles by Tony Fernandez and Pat Borders cut the lead to 6–5.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Roger Mason relieved Greene and after a groundout and walk, Devon White's two-run single put Toronto up 7–6, but the Phillies tied the game in the fourth when Dykstra doubled with two outs off Al Leiter and scored on Mariano Duncan's single.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Next inning, after a leadoff single, Darren Daulton's two-run home run put the Phillies up 9–7.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] After another single, Thompson's RBI double made it 10–7, then Dykstra's second home run of the game made it 12–7 Phillies.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the sixth, White hit a leadoff double before scoring on Roberto Alomar's single off David West.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] After a single and hit-by-pitch loaded the bases, Fernandez's RBI groundout cut the Phillies' lead to 12–9, but they added a run in the bottom half when Dave Hollins hit a leadoff double off Tony Castillo and scored on Thompson's two-out single.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Next inning, a hit-by-pitch to Daulton with the bases loaded made it 14–9 Phillies.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the eighth, though, after a one-out single and walk off Larry Andersen, Molitor's RBI double made it 14–10 Phillies.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Fernandez then hit an RBI single off Mitch Williams.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] A walk loaded the bases, then after a strikeout, Rickey Henderson's single and White's triple scored two runs each to put Toronto ahead 15–14.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Duane Ward earned the save, retiring the last four Phillies batters.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Three new World Series records were set, including the longest game (4:14), most total runs scored in a single game (29), and most runs scored by a losing team (14).
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Also, Charlie Williams became the first African American to serve as the home plate umpire for a World Series game.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Two death threats directed towards Mitch Williams were phoned into Veterans Stadium as soon as it became evident that Williams was going to be the losing pitcher of Game 4.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Williams was not aware of the death threats until after Game 5.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The offenses were due for an off-day, and it came in Game 5 courtesy of a Curt Schilling (Philadelphia) and Juan Guzman (Toronto) pitching duel.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] With the Phillies' backs to the wall, Schilling shut down the previously unstoppable Toronto offense, limiting the team to just five hits, three walks, no extra-base hits (although catcher Pat Borders had two hits) and no runs in a complete-game shutout.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] It was only the second time all season that Toronto had been shut out.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Guzman pitched well in a losing effort, allowing only two runs and five hits in seven innings of work.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The two runs scored as a result of scrappy baserunning play from the Philadelphia offense.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the first inning, Lenny Dykstra walked, stole second, moved to third on a Pat Borders throwing error during the steal, and scored on a John Kruk ground out.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the second inning, Darren Daulton opened with a double, took third on a groundout, and scored on a Kevin Stocker single.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] As it turned out, it was the final postseason baseball game in Veterans Stadium.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] It was demolished after the 2003 season.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The sixth game in the Series was a rematch between Game 2 starters Terry Mulholland and Dave Stewart, who would have similar results.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Toronto scored in the bottom of the first with a run-scoring Paul Molitor triple after a walk, Joe Carter sacrifice fly to score Molitor, and Roberto Alomar RBI single after a double.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Phillies got on the board in the fourth when Darren Daulton doubled with two outs and scored on Jim Eisenreich's single, but the Blue Jays got that run back in the bottom of the inning when Alomar hit a leadoff double, moved to third on a groundout and scored on Ed Sprague Jr.'s sacrifice fly.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Paul Molitor added a home run in the fifth inning while the Toronto fans were chanting "MVP" for Paul, bringing the score to 5–1 for Toronto.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Molitor became the first player in World Series history to have at least two home runs, two doubles, and two triples.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the seventh inning, Philadelphia fought back with five runs.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] After a walk and single, Lenny Dykstra hit a three-run home run to knock Stewart out of the game.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Mariano Duncan singled off reliever Danny Cox, stole second, and scored on Dave Hollins's RBI single to tie the game.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] A walk and single loaded the bases before Pete Incaviglia hit a sacrifice fly to put the Phillies up 6–5.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays would try to threaten in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] John Olerud drew a one-out walk and the Phillies brought in Larry Andersen to face Roberto Alomar.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] After Alomar grounded out, Andersen then hit Tony Fernandez with a pitch and walked Ed Sprague Jr. to load the bases.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Andersen got out of the inning by inducing a pop-fly to Pat Borders.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] This became significant in the next inning, with the batting order reset to the top with Rickey Henderson leading off.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Philadelphia closer Mitch Williams came on to pitch the bottom of the ninth with his team clinging to a 6–5 lead.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] After beginning the inning by walking Rickey Henderson, Williams tried to counter Henderson's speed by using a slide-step style of pitching delivery.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Prior to the game, Williams had never used the slide-step delivery in his career, and this may have cut back on his velocity.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The walk to Henderson was followed by a Devon White flyout and a Paul Molitor single that moved Henderson to second.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Joe Carter came up next and, with the count 2–2, he hit a three-run home run to win the game and the World Series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Just before the fifth and final pitch to Joe Carter, CBS Sports announcer Tim McCarver commented that Carter (relatively unproductive in the Series to date) looked awkward and uncomfortable at the plate.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The same pitch allowed Blue Jays radio announcer Tom Cheek the opportunity to utter his famous "Touch 'em all, Joe" quote, when Joe Carter clinched the series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Carter joined Bill Mazeroski as the only two players to win a World Series with a home run in the bottom of the ninth inning (Mazeroski hit his home run in the deciding Game 7, while Carter hit his in Game 6).
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Carter was actively involved in the final play of the World Series for the second year in a row.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] In the previous year, Carter caught the final out as first baseman after relief pitcher Mike Timlin fielded Otis Nixon's bunt.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Taking the 1993 ALCS into account (where he caught the final out in the outfield), he had been involved in the final play of three straight postseason championship series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] American League president Bobby Brown presented the World Series Trophy instead of the Commissioner of Baseball; this event also occurred in the year before.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays became the second expansion team to win two World Series championships, following the New York Mets in 1986.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] This has since been achieved by the Florida Marlins in 2003, the Kansas City Royals in 2015, and the Houston Astros in 2022.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] With the Montreal Canadiens winning the 1993 Stanley Cup Final five months earlier, it marked the only time Canadian teams won multiple league championships among the four major North American team sports in a calendar year.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] —Mitch Williams on his feelings about surrendering the home run to Joe Carter.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Roger Angell's review of the World Series in *The New Yorker* was entitled "Oh, What a Lovely War".
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] When Joe Carter appeared in the 1996 All-Star Game at Veterans Stadium, he was booed by the crowd for his aforementioned home run that won him this World Series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Both teams would experience absences from the postseason; the Phillies did not return to the postseason until 2007, or appear in another World Series until their championship season of 2008, bringing the city of Philadelphia its first championship since the 76ers swept the 1983 NBA Finals.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The general manager of the Blue Jays, Pat Gillick, was general manager of the Phillies team that won the 2008 World Series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays did not qualify for the playoffs again until the 2015 season.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] This was the last time a Toronto team made it to the championship round in one of the four major sports until the Toronto Raptors in their 2019 championship season.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays would not return to the World Series until 2025, when they ultimately lost to the Los Angeles Dodgers in a seven-game thriller.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] By accumulating 45 runs over the course of the series, the Blue Jays scored the highest number of runs of *any* series-winning team in World Series history.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Only the series-losing 1960 New York Yankees accumulated more runs in a series (55).
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Coincidentally, that series also ended on a walk-off home run.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] 1993 was the last postseason played under a two-division, two post-season round format.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] After the season, MLB owners agreed to a new three-division setup, with extra post-season round (League Division Series).
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The extra round format had been used once before during the 1981 strike shortened season.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] CBS Sports covered the World Series on television for the fourth consecutive year; it was also the final World Series in CBS's contract to air Major League Baseball games.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] For the second consecutive year, Sean McDonough served as lead announcer, with Tim McCarver serving as analyst for the fourth consecutive year.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Pregame and postgame shows saw Andrea Joyce and Pat O'Brien as hosts, while Lesley Visser and Jim Gray were field level reporters.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] CBS Radio was once again the nationwide radio partner (in the US) for the World Series.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Vin Scully led the broadcast for a fourth consecutive year, with Johnny Bench serving as analyst for the fifth and last time.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] John Rooney served as the pregame and postgame show host.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The game was heard on radio throughout Canada on a series of stations picking up the feed of CJCL-AM in Toronto, with the game being called by Jerry Howarth and Tom Cheek.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Cheek's famous call of the Carter home run ("Touch 'em all Joe, you'll never hit a bigger home run in your life!") lives on in Blue Jays folklore.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Tom Cheek never called another postseason game in his role as voice of the Blue Jays, from which he retired in 2005 prior to his death from brain cancer.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Locally in Philadelphia, the World Series was called on WOGL-AM by Harry Kalas, Richie Ashburn, Chris Wheeler, Andy Musser, and Garry Maddox.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The 1993 series was Richie Ashburn's last as a Phillies broadcaster, as he died in 1997.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Andy Musser also called his last World Series as a member of the Phillies' broadcast team; he retired in 2001 and died eleven years later.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Game 6 also marked Johnny Bench's final broadcast for CBS Radio after nine years (he would be replaced on CBS Radio's World Series broadcasts by Jeff Torborg), while Harry Kalas would not call another World Series until 2008.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Kalas later died in 2009 prior to a game at Nationals Park in Washington, D.C.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Chris Wheeler continued to call games for the Phillies until being released in 2014 and Jerry Howarth continued to call Blue Jays games, moving into the primary play-by-play position following the death of Cheek, until his retirement before the 2018 season.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Howarth would return to call postseason games when the Blue Jays qualified in 2015 and 2016, where they were eliminated in the ALCS both years.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Fastball, it's hit to left field, down the line, in the corner, home run!
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Joe Carter, who took the 2 and 0 pitch for a strike right down the middle, hits the 2 and 1 (sic) pitch over the left field wall and the Toronto Blue Jays come back with 3 in the bottom of the ninth inning to become the World Champions yet again.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The final score: Toronto 8, Philadelphia 6.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Trying to lay off that ball, low to the outside part of the plate, he just went after one.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Here's a pitch on the way, a swing and a belt, left field, way back...
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The Blue Jays are World Series champions, as Joe Carter hits a three-run home run in the ninth inning and the Blue Jays have repeated as World Series champions!
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] You'll never hit a bigger home run in your life!
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The 2–2 pitch, line drive in deep left, this ball is outta here.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Three-run home run, Joe Carter, and the Toronto Blue Jays are the world champions of baseball for the second straight year.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] A three-run home run in the bottom of the ninth by Joe Carter who's being mobbed at home plate.
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Well-hit down the left-field line, way back and GONE!
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The winners and still world champions, the Toronto Blue Jays!
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] Toronto rapper Choclair refers to Joe Carter's walk-off home run in his 1999 song, "Let's Ride".
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] On July 29, 2015, Toronto rapper Drake released a diss track against Philadelphia rapper Meek Mill entitled "Back to Back".
[src:1993-world-series/1993-world-series] The cover of the diss track features a picture of Joe Carter, just after hitting the series-clinching home run.
